pwhm: drop the max-capacity zeroing + right-size copy in the driver station pull

Every wld station-stats poll (getStationStats() and the lean
getStationStatsBrief() added in patch 0902 both go through this) ends in a
driver sample pull: wld_ap_nl80211_getAllStationsInfo() ->
wld_nl80211_getAllStationsInfo() -> NL80211_CMD_GET_STATION netlink dump. That
bulk pull does two avoidable things per call:

  1. It calloc-ZEROES a max-capacity receive buffer of
     MAXNROF_STAENTRY (= wld_getMaxNrSta()+1, bumped to the configured max --
     114+ in the scaling test) wld_nl80211_stationInfo_t structs. That struct is
     large (it carries linksInfo[WLD_NL80211_MAX_MLO_LINKS=4] and per-chain
     rssiDbmByChain[MAX_NR_ANTENNA] / rssiAvgDbmByChain[MAX_NR_ANTENNA]), so this
     is tens of KB memset to 0 every poll -- of which only the live nrStation
     slots are ever written or read.

  2. It then calloc's a SECOND, nrStation-sized buffer and memcpy's the live
     slots into it before freeing the receive buffer, purely to "right-size" the
     result -- a full second per-station copy on every poll.

Both are pure overhead and removable with ZERO observable behaviour change.

Fix (one function, wld_nl80211_getAllStationsInfo()):
  - calloc -> malloc for the receive buffer: the dump never reads the unused
    tail, so zeroing it is wasted (proof below).
  - Drop the right-size copy: transfer ownership of the receive buffer directly
    to the caller (*ppStationInfo = receive buffer; *pnStation = nrStation). The
    function now does ONE allocation, NO zeroing and NO second memcpy. The
    returned buffer is MAXNROF_STAENTRY-capacity but the caller only ever reads
    [0, nrStation) and frees the whole thing, so its capacity is invisible.
  - The two edge paths are preserved exactly: nrStation == 0 keeps
    rc = SWL_RC_OK, leaves *ppStationInfo untouched and frees the unused buffer;
    a count-only / NULL-out-param caller also frees the buffer (no leak).

Zero-behaviour-change proof -- every slot a caller can read is fully written:
  - s_getStationInfoCb() memsets a stack stationInfo to 0, parses into it, then
    memcpy's the WHOLE struct into pStationInfo[nrStation] and increments. So
    slots [0, nrStation) are each a complete, fully-initialised struct --
    identical to what calloc would have produced then overwritten.
  - Slots [nrStation, MAXNROF_STAENTRY) are never written and never read: each
    consumer bounds its loop by nrStation and the count is returned out-of-band;
    nothing infers length from the allocation or scans for a sentinel.
  - malloc returning NULL behaves exactly as calloc returning NULL did today: the
    callback guards pStationInfo == NULL, so nrStation stays 0 and the function
    returns SWL_RC_OK with no data via the nrStation == 0 path (free(NULL) is a
    no-op). And nrStation > 0 now implies the malloc succeeded, so the ownership
    transfer is always a valid non-NULL pointer -- which is also why the old
    "second calloc failed -> SWL_RC_ERROR" path simply ceases to exist (there is
    no second allocation to fail; the data is already in hand).

Caller audit (the assumption was "one caller"; grep finds TWO -- both verified
safe, neither reads past nrStation, both free the buffer regardless of size):
  - src/nl80211/wld_ap_nl80211.c:144 (wld_ap_nl80211_getAllStationsInfo) loops
    bounded by nrStation, copies the matching subset, then W_SWL_FREE()s the
    returned buffer.
  - src/nl80211/wld_ep_nl80211.c:134 (wld_ep_nl80211_findStationInfo, pMac==NULL
    branch) loops bounded by nrStation, memcpy's one matching struct, then
    W_SWL_FREE()s the returned buffer.

This does NOT touch the per-station parse/fill work, the single-station path
(wld_nl80211_getStationInfo, its calloc(1) is negligible), the filter-copy in
wld_ap_nl80211_getAllStationsInfo, or the multiple independent dumps from the
other call sites -- those are separate, behaviour-affecting changes left for
later. It is the small, provably-safe win that benefits both the full
getStationStats() and the lean getStationStatsBrief() reply paths.

Upstream-Status: Pending

--- a/src/nl80211/wld_nl80211_api.c
+++ b/src/nl80211/wld_nl80211_api.c
@@ -660,7 +660,13 @@
     struct getStationData_s requestData = {
         .nrStationMax = MAXNROF_STAENTRY,
         .nrStation = 0,
-        .pStationInfo = calloc(MAXNROF_STAENTRY, sizeof(wld_nl80211_stationInfo_t)),
+        /* PPW-XXXX: malloc, not calloc. The dump callback (s_getStationInfoCb)
+         * fully writes every slot it hands back -- it memsets a stack stationInfo
+         * to 0, parses into it, then memcpy's the whole struct into
+         * pStationInfo[nrStation] -- so the [0, nrStation) slots are complete and
+         * the [nrStation, MAXNROF_STAENTRY) tail is never read by any consumer.
+         * Zeroing MAXNROF_STAENTRY of these large structs up front is pure waste. */
+        .pStationInfo = malloc(MAXNROF_STAENTRY * sizeof(wld_nl80211_stationInfo_t)),
     };

     swl_rc_ne rc = wld_nl80211_sendCmdSync(state, NL80211_CMD_GET_STATION, NLM_F_DUMP, ifIndex, NULL, s_getStationInfoCb, &requestData);
@@ -668,17 +674,24 @@
     if(requestData.nrStation == 0) {
         SAH_TRACEZ_NOTICE(ME, "no Station device with ifIndex(%d)", ifIndex);
         rc = SWL_RC_OK;
+        free(requestData.pStationInfo);
     } else if((ppStationInfo != NULL) && (pnStation != NULL)) {
-        *ppStationInfo = calloc(requestData.nrStation, sizeof(wld_nl80211_stationInfo_t));
-        if(*ppStationInfo == NULL) {
-            SAH_TRACEZ_ERROR(ME, "Fail to allocate memory for station info results");
-            rc = SWL_RC_ERROR;
-        } else {
-            *pnStation = requestData.nrStation;
-            memcpy(*ppStationInfo, requestData.pStationInfo, requestData.nrStation * sizeof(wld_nl80211_stationInfo_t));
-        }
+        /* PPW-XXXX: hand the receive buffer straight to the caller instead of
+         * allocating a second nrStation-sized buffer and memcpy'ing the live
+         * slots into it. nrStation > 0 implies the malloc above succeeded (the
+         * callback only counts a station when pStationInfo != NULL), so this is
+         * always a valid, non-NULL transfer. The caller reads only [0, nrStation)
+         * -- the count is returned out-of-band via *pnStation -- and frees the
+         * whole buffer regardless of its capacity, so returning the
+         * MAXNROF_STAENTRY-capacity buffer is invisible and saves one alloc plus
+         * one full-buffer copy per driver pull. */
+        *ppStationInfo = requestData.pStationInfo;
+        *pnStation = requestData.nrStation;
+    } else {
+        /* PPW-XXXX: caller wanted only the count (or nothing); the data the dump
+         * collected is unused, so free the receive buffer rather than leak it. */
+        free(requestData.pStationInfo);
     }
-    free(requestData.pStationInfo);
     return rc;
 }

